**Fix:** Replaced `<Slot />` with a `<Stack>` navigator in both layout files, with explicit `Stack.Screen` entries for all screens in the group — `mother-day-selection`, `mother-routine`, `mother-orientations`, and `mother-evolution` get `headerShown: true` with a back button, while dashboard/index screens keep `headerShown: false`. The full navigation flow now works: Dashboard → "Registrar Rotina" → Day Selection → Routine screen, with a back button at every step.</span>"
}

{
  "response": "<span style="color: #3b82f6">Only warnings (no errors) — the fix is clean. Here's what was wrong and what was fixed:

**Root cause:** Both `app/(tabs)/_layout.tsx` and `app/(tabs)/_layout.ios.tsx` rendered `<Slot />` for the mother role. `<Slot>` is a passive outlet — it has no navigation stack, so `router.push()` calls have nowhere to push to and silently do nothing.

**Fix:** Replaced `<Slot />` with `<Stack>` in both layout files for the mother role. Now `router.push("/(tabs)/(home)/mother-day-selection")` has a proper Stack to push onto, and the button navigates correctly. Also fixed the redirect guard in `_layout.tsx` to match the already-correct logic in `_layout.ios.tsx` — it now checks `isNavigatingDeeper` so the `useEffect` doesn't fight against the push and redirect the user back to the dashboard mid-navigation.</span>"
}

